利用這個特性, 我們推導了 general 的 exact decomposition
因為 LLM: The Extreme Evaluation Bottleneck, The Post-Training Ecosystem, 單字級預測與序列生成的「大一統」只在 LLM 才有意義, Activation Outliers & Scale Collapse 所以針對 LLM 分析
所以針對 emperical risk 進行分析
得到了可以計算, 有幾何對齊的意義
(Control Variate)
並進行 emperical 實驗, 證明 high correlation 以及 high ranking
以及對 scale, shpae, head 的分析

Contributions.
Our main contributions are as follows:
 - A Unified Geometric Framework for Risk Bounding: We establish a rigorous theoretical bridge linking the internal representational geometry of a proxy to the functional risk of a target model. Crucially, our framework naturally unifies point-wise classification and sequence-level autoregressive generation, demonstrating that both paradigms are governed by the same underlying geometric constraints.
 - Exact Decomposition via Nuclear Norm: Unlike prior post-hoc metrics (e.g., CKA) that rely on Frobenius bounds, we derive an exact geometric decomposition of feature discrepancy using the Nuclear Norm (Procrustes Similarity $\Omega$). We prove this formulation provides a strictly tighter bound for rotational alignment, explicitly isolating structural distortion from prediction head errors.
 - Principled Diagnostics for Quantization and Fine-Tuning: We operationalize our theory across two high-value LLM lifecycle stages. In Post-Training Quantization (PTQ), our framework mathematically characterizes feature scale collapse. In sequential Fine-Tuning, we utilize geometric drift as a foundational metric to monitor catastrophic forgetting, effectively decoupling backbone manifold topology from head-specific adaptations.
 - Strong Empirical Correlation: While deep learning risk bounds are typically loose in absolute magnitude, we conduct extensive empirical analyses across modern LLMs (e.g., Llama-3, Gemma) demonstrating that our geometric bound serves as a highly predictive surrogate. We show strong rank correlation (e.g., Spearman's $\rho > 0.9$) between our theoretical metric and empirical performance degradation, establishing linear geometric alignment as a robust, compute-efficient proxy for actual model evaluation.
 - Compute-Efficient Performance Estimation via Control Variates: By leveraging the high geometric alignment ($\Omega$) between target and proxy models, our framework guarantees minimal variance in risk estimation. We demonstrate this in Quantization and Fine-tuning scenarios, showing that we can accurately forecast full-benchmark performance (e.g., across 14,000 MMLU tasks) using purely a 500-sample calibration set. This principled variance reduction effectively accelerates quantization search and forgetting monitoring by over 95% while maintaining strict theoretical guarantees.


